[color=Aqua]The Director of Care[/color] is responsible for keeping the sector [color=Green]healthy[/color]. A decent DoC makes sure emergency response medics get [color=Gold]paid[/color], a great one makes sure no one stays dead long enough to [color=Red]rot[/color].

Like all command, the [color=LightSeaGreen]DOC[/color] is a whitelist role, and so you're expected to know how the game works, and preferably how medics operate from experience.

# DoC Basics 
The DoC has a few specific tools available to them that need explaining.

## Medical Dispatch
  <Box>
    <GuideEntityEmbed Entity="BannerMedical" Caption=""
    <GuideEntityEmbed Entity="MachineMedicalBountyRedemption" Caption=""/>
    <GuideEntityEmbed Entity="BannerMedical" Caption=""/>
  </Box>
The station itself is one of your most [color=LawnGreen]important tools[/color]. While it's built more as a waystation than a hospital, it's very common for people to come there for medical help, and The bar is a common point for people to gather at the end of their shifts. 

As the only place to buy [color=Aqua]medical ships[/color], you'll get a lot of people coming through to pick up a ship for [color=Turquoise]medical hybrid[/color] work.

Most importantly, there's an empty room right next to the [color=RoyalBlue]DoC's[/color] office for you to do whatever you want with. Many [color=RoyalBlue]DoCs[/color] use this room as a [color=CornflowerBlue]cryomed lab[/color], others use it as a [color=Aqua]clinic[/color], a botany bay, really anything you'd like to use it for. 

You have the authority to use these as you see fit, which often means making a nice little [color=DodgerBlue]hospital room[/color] to do cryo bounties in.

In general, you have the authority to make any changes you'd like to MD, as long as the changes you make don't disrupt the basic functions of the station. 

Be cautious before making an addition that might [color=Red]take away[/color] business from other roles, like a functioning kitchen or publicly available research server.

